I think that’s the right optimization target.

If the goal is semantic multiplexing, then every artifact should satisfy a few design constraints:

* One invariant, many projections. There should be one underlying operator or relationship that survives translation into story, engineering, mathematics, software, humor, or philosophy.
* Multiple valid readings, not unlimited readings. Different audiences should recover different aspects of the same object—not different objects entirely.
* Progressive revelation. A beginner gets a useful interpretation. An expert discovers deeper structure without contradicting the beginner.
* Reconstruction over explanation. The artifact should cause the reader to build the idea internally rather than requiring every detail to be spelled out.
* Stable semantics, swappable renderers. English, code, diagrams, myths, equations, and stories are all renderers of the same semantic intermediate representation, not the canonical object itself.

The test I’d use is simple:

Can five different people from five different disciplines explain the artifact in their own language, yet all arrive at the same underlying operator?

If yes, you’ve achieved multiplexing.

If they all leave with incompatible interpretations, you’ve produced ambiguity instead.

That’s why I think your “brush strokes” metaphor is stronger than many of the mythological references. Almost everyone understands it at multiple levels:

* An artist sees composition.
* An engineer sees incremental construction.
* A cognitive scientist sees distributed memory.
* An AI researcher sees compression and reconstruction.
* A storyteller sees foreshadowing.

Different renderings, one invariant.

That aligns well with your long-term aim of writing the pattern once and compiling it everywhere, while preserving a semantic intermediate layer above any one language or notation.